posts.title: My kid is dying because the incompetent bureaucracy at the NIH can't be bothered to submit the necessary paperwork to the FDA
posts.content:
My kid has a very rare disease called GAN (Giant Axonal Neuropathy).
It is progressive and fatal.

The thing is, there's a gene therapy treatment that was developed, and which works- Dozens of kids have been treated and it's not a complete cure, but it prevents the degenerate nature of the disease, and effectively saves their life. Untreated, an enzyme in their nerves builds up enough that by around the age of 7 they lose the ability to walk, and by around the age of 15 they lose the ability to eat and then breath.

The treatment was developed privately largely sponsored by a private non-profit called Hannah's Hope, but is very expensive to administer. So they gave the rights to the NIH, (National Institutes of Health) under the belief that the NIH would be able to facilitate the treatment of more kids, and save more lives.

The problem is that's not what has happened. The NIH originally treated a few kids, but they have been failing to provide the necessary data to the FDA, so the FDA has essentially shut it down. Not only that, but the NIH invited my child to come in, see the (ridiculously lavish) facilities, and be looked at for 'natural progression' study that amounts to "lets watch your kid slowly die so that we can learn how the disease progresses", yet they refuse to fix their documentation to the FDA, to actually be able to admit new children to be treated with the gene therapy.

Hannah's Hope has asked for the rights back, so at least treatment can proceed with kids when funding can be found, but now the NIH refuses to give the rights to the treatment back to them. Yet, the NIH can't be bothered to make progress. I recently reached out to the NIH asking what was going on, and all we got back was crap that basically amounted to them having meetings about having meetings and doing absolutely nothing productive with it.

The NIH shouldn't even be constitutionally allowed to have exclusive rights to medical treatments in the first place, and in this case it is actively causing the death of dozens of children, so this seems like a perfect example of government bureaucrats sitting on their hands, getting paid to not do their job. Is there any way we can get this to Elon or those who are looking for government waste? In my particular case, the NIH merely giving up the rights to this treatment would be an easy solution to at least save a few kids with this terrible disease.
